The '''Indo-Iranian languages''' or '''Indo-Iranic languages'''<ref name="Mahulkar1990">{{cite book|author=D. D. Mahulkar|title=Pre-Pāṇinian Linguistic Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vsNF-yuHEgYC|year=1990|publisher=Northern Book Centre|isbn=978-81-85119-88-5}}</ref><ref name="PuglielliFrascarelli2011">{{cite book|author1=Annarita Puglielli|author2=Mara Frascarelli|title=Linguistic Analysis: From Data to Theory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OCwJBdGbW-cC|year=2011|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-022250-0}}</ref>, or '''Aryan languages''',<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN3110161133&id=KFBDGWjCP7gC&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&vq=aryan+languages&dq=aryan+languages+iranian&sig=11bYU5iUtJpZx-Ct7VdMBvOjG_c |title=Numeral Types and Changes Worldwide, by Jadranka (EDT) Gvozdanovic, Language Arts & Disciplines,1999, Page 221 |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}: "The usage of 'Aryan languages' is not to be equated with Indo-Aryan languages, rather Indo-Iranic languages of which Indo-Aryan is a subgrouping."</ref> constitute the largest and southeasternmost extant branch of the [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] [[language family]]. It has more than 1.5 billion speakers, stretching from [[Europe]] ([[Romani language|Romani]]), [[Turkey]] ([[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] and [[Zaza–Gorani languages|Zaza–Gorani]]) and the [[Caucasus]] ([[Ossetian language|Ossetian]]) eastward to [[Xinjiang]] ([[Sarikoli language|Sarikoli]]) and [[Assam]] ([[Assamese language|Assamese]]), and south to [[Sri Lanka]] ([[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]]) and the [[Maldives]] ([[Maldivian language|Maldivian]]).

The common ancestor of all of the languages in this family is called [[Proto-Indo-Iranian language|Proto-Indo-Iranian]]—also known as Common Aryan—which was spoken in approximately the late 3rd millennium BC. The three branches of the modern Indo-Iranian languages are [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]], [[Iranian languages|Iranian]], and [[Nuristani languages|Nuristani]]. Additionally, sometimes a fourth independent branch, [[Dardic languages|Dardic]], is posited, but recent scholarship in general places Dardic languages as archaic members of the Indo-Aryan branch.<ref name="jain-cardona-2007">{{Cite encyclopaedia| year = 2007 | title = The Indo-Aryan languages | editor1-first = Danesh | editor1-last = Jain | editor2-first = George | editor2-last = Cardona | page = 905 | quote ='Dardic' is a geographic cover term for those Northwest Indo-Aryan languages which ''[..]'' developed new characteristics different from the IA languages of the Indo-Gangetic plain. Although the Dardic and Nuristani (previously 'Kafiri') languages were formerly grouped together, Morgenstierne (1965) has established that the Dardic languages are Indo-Aryan, and that the Nuristani languages constitute a separate subgroup of Indo-Iranian. | isbn = 978-0415772945 | author-first = Elena | author-last = Bashir }}</ref>

==Languages==
[[File:Indo-Iranian languages.png|thumb|Chart classifying Indo-Iranian languages within the Indo-European language family]]
[[File:Lenguas indoiranias.PNG|thumb|Indo-Iranian languages]]
The Indo-Iranian languages consist of three groups: 
* [[Indo-Aryan languages]]
* [[Iranian languages|Iranian/Iranic]]
* [[Nuristani languages|Nuristani]]

{{Indo-European topics}}

Most of the largest languages (in terms of speakers) are a part of the Indo-Aryan group: [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] (Urdu, ~590 million<ref>{{cite web|last=Edwards|first=Viv|title=Urdu Today|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/voices/multilingual/urdu.shtml|publisher=BBC}}</ref>), [[Bengali language|Bengali]] (205 million<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Irene|title=Bengali|url=http://aboutworldlanguages.com/bengali|publisher=AboutWorldLanguages|accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref>), [[Bishnupuriya]] (12 million)<ref> http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Census_Data_Online/Language/statement9.htm</ref>, [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] (100 million), [[Marathi language|Marathi]] (75 million), [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] (50 million), [[Bhojpuri language|Bhojpuri]] (40 million), [[Awadhi language|Awadhi]] (40 million), [[Maithili language|Maithili]] (35 million), [[Odia language|Odia]] (35 million), [[Marwari language|Marwari]] (30 million), [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] (25 million), [[Assamese language|Assamese]] (24 million), [[Rajasthani language|Rajasthani]] (20 million), [[Chhattisgarhi language|Chhattisgarhi]] (18 million), [[Sinhalese language|Sinhalese]] (19 million), [[Nepali language|Nepali]] (17 million), and [[Rangpuri language|Rangpuri]] (15 million). Among the Iranian branch, major languages are [[Persian language|Persian]] (60 million), [[Pashto language|Pashto]] (ca. 50 million), [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] (35 million),<ref name=CIA1>CIA- The World Factbook: 14.7 million in Turkey (18%)[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tu.html]{{not in citation|date=February 2016}}, 4.9–6.5 million in Iraq (15-20%)[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/iz.html]{{not in citation|date=February 2016}}, 8 million in Iran (10%){{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203093100/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |archivedate=3 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}{{not in citation|date=February 2016}} (all for 2014), plus several million in Syria, neighboring countries, and the diaspora</ref> and [[Balochi language|Balochi]] (8 million), with a total number of native speakers of more than 1471 million. Numerous smaller languages exist.

==History==
The common [[proto-language]] of the Indo-Iranian languages is [[Proto-Indo-Iranian]], which has been reconstructed.

The oldest attested Indo-Iranian languages are [[Vedic Sanskrit]] (ancient Indo-Aryan), Older and Younger [[Avestan language|Avestan]] and [[Old Persian language|Old Persian]] (ancient Iranian languages). A few words from another Indo-Aryan language (see [[Indo-Aryan superstrate in Mitanni]]) are attested in documents from the ancient [[Mitanni]] and [[Hittites|Hittite]] kingdoms in the Near East.
{{clear}}

==Features==
Innovations shared with other languages affected by the [[satem]] sound changes include: {{cn|date=August 2015}}
* Fronting and [[assibilation]] of the Proto-Indo-European (PIE) palato-velar stops: {{PIE|*kʲ, *gʲʰ, *gʲ > *t͡ʃ, *d͡ʒʰ, *d͡ʒ}}
* The merger of the PIE labiovelar and plain velar stops: {{PIE|*kʷ, *gʷʰ, *gʷ > *k, *gʰ, *g}}
* The [[Ruki sound law]]

Innovations shared with Greek include: {{cn|date=August 2015}}
* The vocalization of the PIE syllabic nasals {{PIE|*m̥, *n̥}} to {{PIE|*a}}
* [[Grassmann's law]]

Innovations unique to Indo-Iranian include: {{cn|date=August 2015}}
* The lowering of PIE {{PIE|*e}} to {{PIE|*a}}
** *o was also lowered to *a, though this occurred in several other Indo-European languages as well.
* [[Brugmann's law]]
